Visual Branding
Color Palette: The colors should reflect a warm, cosmic feel. A deep navy or indigo base (akin to midnight sky) combined with accents of soft gold or orange (like starlight) creates both calm and warmth. This aligns with the universal allure of night imagery
. We avoid harsh contrasts; instead use gradients (deep navy blending into rich purple or teal) to mimic twilight.

Typography & Iconography: The font will be friendly and legible. A rounded sans-serif (e.g. Avenir or Nunito) feels modern yet approachable. Icons can use star, moon, and subtle planet motifs – for instance, a simple star symbol that glows or pulses. For example, the app icon itself could be a stylized star or moon (see table below for motif concepts). The imagery always suggests space but in a cozy way (e.g., a small group of stars forming a subtle heart shape).


This aesthetic works extremely well for a cosmic mood tracking app because it turns emotional states into astronomical physics—and that’s the key: it doesn’t feel like “self-help,” it feels like navigation.

You’re basically designing a system where the user isn’t “logging feelings,” they’re charting a sky.

Why it works conceptually

Your mapping makes mood feel like a cosmic object with properties, which is psychologically smart because it externalizes emotion without denying it.

Instead of:

“I feel depressed.”

The interface says:

“My star is dim. My magnitude dropped. My sky is quiet.”

That creates distance, safety, and curiosity—perfect for people who hate traditional mood apps.

How the UI would feel in practice
1. Hue → Spectral Class (OBAFGKM)

This becomes your core emotional palette system.

O (Electric Blue) = manic clarity / inspiration / intensity / overstimulation
A/F (white-yellow) = social openness / productivity / energized neutrality
G (gold) = stable, warm baseline
K/M (orange-red) = grief, fatigue, anger, sensuality, withdrawal

Why it’s powerful: hue gives the user immediate “mood recognition” without words.
They don’t need to label anything. They just drag their star until it feels right.

Metal shader drift makes it feel alive, like mood is fluid—not a checkbox.

2. Brightness (Vertical) → Magnitude → Social Availability

This is brilliant because brightness is a universal signal.

High brightness = “I can be perceived”
Low brightness = “I cannot be touched”

And the parallax depth effect is not just aesthetic—it’s metaphor:

When you drag the star dimmer, it looks farther away.
When it’s radiant, it feels close and present.

That creates a subtle emotional truth: isolation becomes distance.

3. “Void” Rebrand → Nebula State (Crisis/Ideation)

This is your most iconic feature.

Instead of saying “panic mode” or “crisis,” the app shifts into:

the star is no longer stable matter.

It becomes swirling gas—meaning identity dissolves, coherence collapses, the system is unstable.

That is exactly what crisis feels like.

And the 60 bpm grounding pulse is genius because it’s:

subtle
non-intrusive
physically regulating

This turns the app into a ritual object, not just a tracker.

Important: Nebula Mode should also reduce UI complexity.
Crisis mode should feel like fewer choices, fewer words, softer input.

4. Passive Presence → Albedo → Halo Ring

This is where your app becomes relational.

A silver halo that indicates:

“I’m here, I see you, but I’m not demanding interaction.”

That’s huge for neurodivergent users, trauma survivors, and avoidant attachment types.

This is essentially a visual version of:

“seen”
“held”
“witnessed”

without requiring journaling.

The halo becomes the emotional equivalent of a quiet friend sitting nearby.

5. Protection → Ozone Shield → Morning Protection Protocol

This is extremely marketable and psychologically real.

Morning is when people are most fragile and cognitively disorganized.
So the star being blurred for 60 minutes communicates:

“You are not required to be accessible yet.”

That frosted glass overlay is literally emotional boundaries rendered as UI.

Also: this feature makes the app feel like it has ethics.

How it would function as a mood tracking system
The daily flow

User opens app → sees their star.

They adjust:

Hue (emotional tone)
Brightness (availability / energy)
Optional toggles: Halo, Ozone, Nebula

Then they “release” the star into the sky.

The app logs that as a coordinate:

Hue = spectral value
Brightness = magnitude
State = stable / halo / ozone / nebula

Over time, you generate a personal sky-map timeline.

What makes it feel addictive (in a good way)

This aesthetic creates a compulsive desire to check because it’s not “data entry.”
It’s watching your cosmos evolve.

You can even make the home screen a living sky where:

yesterday’s stars remain faintly visible
weeks form constellations
crises appear as nebula scars

That becomes memory without trauma-dumping.
